The reaction was carried out by adding (0,0.02, 0.05, 0.08, 0.1) g of 1, 8-ethylenediaminonaphthalene diamine modified cellulose and (0.1, 0.08, 0.05, 0.02, 0) g of microcrystalline cellulose to 10 mL of 68 % zinc chloride solution, respectively, with stirring and clarification. 0.02 g MBA and 0.04 g APS was added to continue the reaction, and 3 mL acrylic acid was added and stirred for 5 min, and heated at 60 °C for 30 min to obtain different proportions of CENAEA/PAA hydrogel. The specific experimental reagent dosage is shown in Table 1
                        . They were named CENAEA0/PAA, CENAEA0.02/PAA, CENAEA0.05/PAA, CENAEA0.08/PAA, CENAEA0.1/PAA (Scheme 1
                        ).

Based on the abovementioned results, the Cr(VI) adsorption and detection mechanism of the CENAEA/PAA can be as follows (Fig. 8
                           ). Firstly, because the porous structures of the CENAEA/PAA served as the mass transfer channel, Cr(VI) were quickly moved from the surface to the inside area. Then the formation of aggregates between the hydrogel network and Cr(VI). When Cr(VI) was added to the hydrogel, due to electrostatic adsorption or chelating effects, CENAEA/PAA/Cr(VI) aggregates form and charge transfer occurs, leading to quenching of CENAEA/PAA. This is also illustrated by the FT-IR and UV variations of the hydrogel after the addition of Cr(VI), as shown in Fig. S4. and Fig. S5., with characteristic peaks of CN and CN at 1695 cm−1 and 1448 cm−1, respectively. As the Cr(VI) content increases, the CN and CN vibrations are gradually weakened and the characteristic groups of the CENAEA fluorophore are gradually weakened, resulting in a gradual quenching of the fluorescence. Furthermore, combining the isotherms and adsorption kinetics results in Fig. 10, Tables 2 and 3

                           , it can be seen that the amide groups bind to the cellulose by grafting, while the metal ions attach to the functional groups by electrostatic attraction and electron sharing or exchange to form chelates [36,37]. Thus, the adsorption of Cr(VI) on CENAEA/PAA hydrogels was realised.
